evaluation_questions.question: Find papers about protein quantification methods

expected_evidence.expected_result: Papers on Bradford assay, Lowry method, and other protein quantification techniques
expected_evidence.expected_ai_response: Based on the search results, I found several important papers on protein quantification methods. The most significant include the Lowry protein assay method (W1775749144) and the Bradford protein assay (W2128635872, W4293247451). These are fundamental techniques in biochemistry for measuring protein concentration, with the Lowry method using Folin phenol reagent and the Bradford method using Coomassie dye binding. Both methods are widely used in laboratories for protein analysis and have been cited extensively in the scientific literature.

evaluation_questions.question: Research on deep learning architectures for computer vision

expected_evidence.expected_result: Papers on deep residual networks and related computer vision architectures
expected_evidence.expected_ai_response: The search results include significant research on deep learning architectures for computer vision, particularly the ResNet paper (W2194775991) by Kaiming He and colleagues on 'Deep Residual Learning for Image Recognition'. This work introduced residual networks with skip connections, which solved the vanishing gradient problem in very deep networks and achieved breakthrough performance on ImageNet. ResNet architectures have become foundational in computer vision, enabling training of networks with hundreds of layers and significantly advancing the field of deep learning for image recognition tasks.

evaluation_questions.question: Studies on gene expression analysis and quantitative methods

expected_evidence.expected_result: Papers on quantitative gene expression analysis methods
expected_evidence.expected_ai_response: The search results include important work on quantitative gene expression analysis, particularly the paper by Livak and Schmittgen (W2107277218) on 'Analysis of Relative Gene Expression Data Using Real-Time Quantitative PCR'. This work describes the widely-used 2^(-ΔΔCt) method for analyzing relative gene expression data from qPCR experiments. These quantitative methods are fundamental for measuring RNA levels and understanding gene regulation in molecular biology research.
